%U A391234 9280523146533806331987399720,58094384066172033744456805634550,374253836760702740599317449688465810,2468122083457731896636582178758135814672
%N A391234 Diagonal of the 3-dimensional geode array: a(n) = G(n,n,n).
%C A391234 The Geode G is a 3-dimensional array of positive integers introduced by Wildberger and Rubine (2025) via operator inversion of the hyper-Catalan generating series. For the 3-dimensional geode, S - 1 = (t_2 + t_3 + t_4) * G where S is the hyper-Catalan series in variables t_2, t_3, t_4. This sequence records the main diagonal a(n) = G(n,n,n).
%C A391234 Every entry G(m2,m3,m4) can be expressed as a closed-form alternating binomial sum of hyper-Catalan numbers (Kotlarz, 2026): G(m2,m3,m4) = Sum_{i=0..m3} Sum_{j=0..m4} (-1)^{i+j} * C(i+j,i) * C(m2+1+i+j, m3-i, m4-j), where C(m2,m3,m4) = (S+L-1)!/(m2!*m3!*m4!*L!) with S = m2+m3+m4, L = m2+2*m3+3*m4+1.
%C A391234 Combinatorial interpretation: G(m2,m3,m4) counts exactly the ballot sequences (Lukasiewicz words) of type (m2+1,m3,m4) in which the first negative step is -1. Equivalently, no step of value -k (k >= 2) precedes the first step of value -1. Equivalently, in the corresponding ordered tree, no node of arity r >= 3 whose first r-2 children are all leaves precedes the first binary node in pre-order.
%C A391234 Amdeberhan, Kauers, and Zeilberger (arXiv:2508.10245) found a second-order holonomic recurrence for this sequence with degree-35 polynomial coefficients.
%H A391234 T. Amdeberhan, M. Kauers, and D. Zeilberger, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.10245">The Challenge of Computing Geode Numbers</a>, arXiv:2508.10245 [math.CO], 2025; Palestine J. Math. 14(4) (2025), 709-713.
%H A391234 T. Amdeberhan and D. Zeilberger, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17862">Proofs Of Three Geode Conjectures</a>, arXiv:2506.17862 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A391234 I. M. Gessel, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.09405">Lattice Paths and the Geode</a>, arXiv:2507.09405 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A391234 M. Gossow, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.18097">Ordered Trees and the Geode</a>, arXiv:2507.18097 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A391234 D. Rubine, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.21785">Computing the 4D Geode</a>, arXiv:2512.21785 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A391234 D. Rubine, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.04552">Hyper-Catalan and Geode Recurrences and Three Conjectures of Wildberger</a>, arXiv:2507.04552 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A391234 N. J. Wildberger and D. Rubine, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/00029890.2025.2460966">A Hyper-Catalan Series Solution to Polynomial Equations, and the Geode</a>, Amer. Math. Monthly, 132(5) (2025), 420-437.
%F A391234 a(n) = G(n,n,n) where G(m2,m3,m4) = Sum_{i=0..m3} Sum_{j=0..m4} (-1)^{i+j} * binomial(i+j,i) * C(m2+1+i+j, m3-i, m4-j), where C(m2,m3,m4) = (S+L-1)!/(m2!*m3!*m4!*L!) with S = m2+m3+m4, L = m2+2*m3+3*m4+1.
%F A391234 Equivalently, G satisfies the recurrence G(m2,m3,m4) = C(m2+1,m3,m4) - G(m2+1,m3-1,m4) - G(m2+1,m3,m4-1) (indices below 0 give 0).
%o A391234 (Python)
%o A391234 from math import factorial
%o A391234 def C(m2, m3, m4):
%o A391234     S, L = m2+m3+m4, m2+2*m3+3*m4+1
%o A391234     return factorial(S+L-1) // (factorial(m2)*factorial(m3)*factorial(m4)*factorial(L))
%o A391234 def a(n):
%o A391234     res = 0
%o A391234     for i in range(n+1):
%o A391234         for j in range(n+1):
%o A391234             t = factorial(i+j)//(factorial(i)*factorial(j)) * C(n+1+i+j, n-i, n-j)
%o A391234             res += t if (i+j)%2==0 else -t
%o A391234     return res
%o A391234 print([a(n) for n in range(12)])
%o A391234 (PARI) C(m2,m3,m4) = my(S=m2+m3+m4, L=m2+2*m3+3*m4+1); (S+L-1)!/(m2!*m3!*m4!*L!);
%o A391234 a(n) = sum(i=0, n, sum(j=0, n, (-1)^(i+j) * binomial(i+j,i) * C(n+1+i+j, n-i, n-j))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Mar 16 2026
